{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5fc5e932-62aa-4ea7-a856-a6b02a8b455c","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` ties a service's lifetime to an **HTTP request** — each request gets a fresh instance. MAUI has no equivalent automatic scope boundary. Without an explicit scope, `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton` — one instance lives for the entire app lifetime.\n\n**Fix options:**\n\n1. **Create scopes manually** when navigating:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = serviceProvider.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Use `AddTransient`** if you want a new DbContext every time it's resolved.\n\n3. **Create a scope per page** by resolving pages from a new `IServiceScope` in your navigation logic.\n\nThe core takeaway: MAUI doesn't create per-request scopes automatically, so you must define your own scope boundaries or switch to transient registration.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e315312a-fa8a-441f-8c97-a883a5108b8f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common issue when transitioning from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to look at any code.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request (each request is a \"scope\"). In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request, so the default scope is essentially the entire application lifetime — making `AddScoped` behave like `AddSingleton`.\n\nI can answer this directly without tools.","outputTokens":361,"requestId":"482C:386B3C:542B104:5C62884:69F3FD0E"},"id":"43ed3d42-bfb0-40a9-810f-1e77593b3f8a","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:08:40.735Z","parentId":"2ded0e29-2eb8-43e2-b7de-a76a4c7f2439"}
